what their characters will do, including and casting of spells.\000\000\0003.\000 Initiative is determined.\000\000\0004.\000 Attacks are made in order of initiative.\000\000\000These steps are followed until the combat ends--either one side is defeated, surrenders, or runs away.\000\000\000NPC/Monster Determination:\000 \000In the first step, the DM secretly decides in general terms what each opponent will do, such as attack, flee, or cast a spell. He does not announce his decisions to the players. If a spell is to be cast, the DM picks the spell before the players announce their characters' actions.\000\0005\002\000\000\376\001\000\000\340\307\031\000!\315\031\0007\000\000\000 <\200\375\003\000\200\000\0004\002\212\230\232\206\0300`\200\001\000\203\200\015\000\200\004\000\200\001\000\202\203\202\377\000\000\000Player Determination:\000 \000Next, the players give a general indication of what their characters are planning to do. This does not have to be perfectly precise and can be changed somewhat if the DM decides that circumstances warrant.\000\000If the characters are battling goblins, a player can say, "My fighter will attack" without announcing which goblin he will strike. If the characters are battling a mixed group of goblins and ogres, the player has to state whether his character is attacking goblins or ogres.\000\000n\002\000\000@\002\000\000\354\312\031\000\217\317\031\000.\000\000\000 *\200\201\004\000\200\000\0004\002\212\230\232\206\0300`\200\001\000\203\202\203\202\377\000\000Spells to be cast must also be announced at this time and cannot be changed once the initiative die is rolled. In any situation where the abilities of a character could make a difference, a clear description must be given.\000\000Before moving on, the DM will make sure he has a clear idea of not only what the player characters are doing, but also what actions any hirelings and henchmen are taking. Once he has a clear view of everything that's likely to happen, the DM can overrule any announced action that violates the rules (or in the case of an NPC, is out of character).\000\000{\002\000\0009\002\000\000!\315\031\000\026\002\032\000B\000\000\000 R\200s\004\000\200\000\0004\002\212\230\232\206\0300`\200\001\000\203\202\203\200\015\000\200\004\000\200\001\000\202\203\200\015\000\200\004\000\200\001\000\202\377\000\000He is not required to overrule an impossible \217\317\031\000\026\002\032\000m\305\031\000action, but he can let a character attempt it anyway, knowing full well the character cannot succeed. It is not the DM's position to advise players on the best strategies, most intelligent actions, or optimum maneuvers for their characters.\000\000\000Initiative:\000 \000In the third step, dice are rolled to determine initiative, according to the rules for initiative.\000\000\000Resolution:\000 \000In the last step, PCs, NPCs, and monsters make their attacks, spells occur, and any other actions are resolved according to the order of initiative.\000\000K\003\000\000\025\003\000\000\217\317\031\000a\005\032\0006\000\000\000 :\200+\006\000\200\000\0004\002\212\230\232\206\0300`\200\001\000\203\202\203\202\202\200\013\000\203\202\203\202\377\000\000The above sequence is not immutable. Indeed, some monsters violate the standard sequence, and some situations demand the application of common sense. In these cases the DM's word is final.\000\000Here's an example of the combat sequence in action: \000\000\000\000Rath is leading a party through the corridors of a dungeon. Right behind him are Rupert and Delsenora. Rounding a bend, they see a group of orcs and trolls about 20 feet away. No one is surprised by the encounter.\000\000The DM has notes telling him that the orcs are hesitant. He secretly decides that they will fall back and let the trolls fight. The trolls, able to regenerate, are naturally overconfident and step forward to the front rank (cursing the orcs at the same time). Turning to the players, the DM asks, "What are you going to do?"\