0\200\013\000\200\001\000\202\203\202\377\000\000\000Especially powerful creatures possess innate abilities, magical powers they can use at will. The majority of these function like spells. Thus, a brownie who is able to cause confusion has the same effect as a character who casts the\000 confusion\000 spell. Creatures able to become invisible at will usually use all the normal rules for the\000 invisibility\000 spell.\000\000Innate abilities are different from spells in one major way, however. Unlike spells, innate abilities are natural powers and do not require casting times or any components (although there is an initiative modifier), including gestures or words--unless these things are used for dramatic effect. (The monster casually points to the place where his spell will occur and then looks at the party with a wicked smile.) Innate abilities are activated by the merest mental command of the creature.\000\000t\002\000\000F\002\000\000\233\006\037\000\240\014\037\000.\000\000\000 *\200\215\004\000\200\000\0004\002\212\230\232\206\0300`\200\001\000\203\202\203\202\377\000\000In all other respects, innate abilities function like spells. They have the same range, area of effect, and duration limitations of the spell of the same name. When the spell in question varies in power according to the level of the caster, the creature is assumed to have a level equal to its Hit Dice. If this means the creature is of insufficient level to cast the spell, it uses the spell at the minimum level needed to cast it.\000\000Innate abilities generally can be used just once a round. Further, a creature cannot use an innate ability and make an attack in the same round.\000\000Q\000\000\000\032\000\000\000,\012\037\000\361\014\037\0007\000\000\000 >\2004\000\200\000\0004\002\212\230\232\206\0300`\200\001\000\202\343*\352$\334\200\007\000\211\200\001\000\202\377\000\000\000\000Table of Contents\000\000 \000\000V\000\000\000%\000\000\000\240\014\037\000G\015\037\0001\000\000\000\002\30