00\331\005\000\200\000\0004\002\212\230\232\206\0300`\200\005\000\202\200\001\000\202\203\202\203\202\377\000Voluntarily Failing Saving Throws\000\000\000\000No saving throw is made if the target voluntarily chooses not to resist the effect of a spell or special attack. This is the case even if the character was duped as to the exact nature of the spell. When a character announces that he is not resisting the spell's power, that spell (or whatever) has its full effect.\000\000The intention not to resist must be clearly stated or set up through trickery, however. If a character is attacked by surprise or caught unawares, he is normally allowed a saving throw. The DM can modify this saving throw, making the chance of success worse if the situation warrants it. Only in extreme cases of trickery and deception should an unwitting character be denied a saving throw.\000\000Q\000\000\000\032\000\000\000H\004 \000\270\007 \0007\000\000\000 >\2004\000\200\000\0004\002\212\230\232\206\0300`\200\001\000\202\343*\352$\334\200\007\000\211\200\001\000\202\377\000\000\000\000Table of Contents\000\000 \000\000g\000\000\0006\000\000\000g\007 \000\037\010 \0001\000\000\000\002\350\002\000\000I\002@\000f\007@\000\026\001\000\000\377\377\377\377\037\010 \000\240\012 \000Ability Checks as Saving Throws (Dungeon Master Guide)0\002\000\000\375\001\000\000\270\007 \000O\012 \0003\000\000\000 4\200\373\003\000\200\000\0004\002\212\230\232\206\0300`\200\005\000\202\200\001\000\202\203\202\203\202\377\000Ability Checks as Saving Throws\000\000\000\000When a character attempts to avoid danger through the use of one of his abilities, an ability check can be used in lieu of a saving throw.\000\000For example, Ragnar the thief has broken into someone's home when he hears a grating noise from the ceiling above him. He looks up to find a five-ton block of the ceiling headed straight for him! He is going to need speedy reactions to get out of the way, so a Dexterity ability check should be rolled to